						<summary>

						<p>Impression received from Dr. G.S. Dixit, (4), Karnataka University, Dharwar [Findspot: Korōchi (?) Hatkanangale Taluk, Kolhapur District].</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">1799 A.D. || 1820 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This Jaina record is damaged and speaks of a number of events taking place in stages in between the dates 1799 A.D., and 1820 A.D.</p>						

						<p>It states that the two brothers Rāyappa and Dēvappa, the two sons of a <hi rend="italic">nāyaka</hi> (Narasimha nāyaka) constructed a <hi rend="italic">jinālaya</hi> and consecrated the image of Pārśvanātha and other images probably under the guidance of Jīnasenāchārya, the <hi rend="italic">jīna muni.</hi> The jīnalaya was equipped with <hi rend="italic">prākāra, gōpuradwāra,</hi> māna-sthambha and dhwaja-sthambha. Perhaps this first stage of work was over by the first date of the record (1799 A.D.). Some more works were completed by 1820 A.D. But the information about which is not clear since the record is very much damaged.</p>						

						<p>The two dates in the record are: 1 Śaka 1720, Kālayukta, Māga, Śu [|] Monday. corresponds to 1799 A.D., February 5, Tuesday. 2 Śaka 1742, Vikrama [Mārgśi]ra, śu. 14. It corresponds to 1820 A.D., December 18, Monday.</p>						

						</summary>
